sets

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict sets with group and time_point (formula: sets ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models explanatory power related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is 0.26. The models intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 9.00 (S.E. = 3.86, p = 0.020, 95% CI [1.44, 16.56]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 4.00, S.E. = 4.72, p = 0.397, 95% CI [-5.26, 13.26]; Std. beta = 0.73, 95% CI [-0.96, 2.41])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -3.50, S.E. = 5.45, p = 0.521, 95% CI [-14.19, 7.19]; Std. beta = -0.64, 95% CI [-2.58, 1.31])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -2.50, S.E. = 7.22, p = 0.729, 95% CI [-16.64, 11.64]; Std. beta = -0.45, 95% CI [-3.02, 2.12])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.

The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.42) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.28. The models intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 42.73 (S.E. = 4.28, p < .001, 95% CI [34.34, 51.13]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 4.25, S.E. = 5.24, p = 0.418, 95% CI [-6.03, 14.53]; Std. beta = 0.68, 95% CI [-0.96, 2.31])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -2.70, S.E. = 5.45, p = 0.621, 95% CI [-13.38, 7.99]; Std. beta = -0.43, 95% CI [-2.13, 1.27])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -6.15, S.E. = 7.31, p = 0.400, 95% CI [-20.47, 8.17]; Std. beta = -0.98, 95% CI [-3.26, 1.30])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.

nb_mcs

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict nb_mcs with group and time_point (formula: nb_mcs ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models explanatory power related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is 0.38. The models intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 38.35 (S.E. = 5.20, p < .001, 95% CI [28.16, 48.54]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.06, S.E. = 6.37, p = 0.992, 95% CI [-12.54, 12.42]; Std. beta = -7.37e-03, 95% CI [-1.51, 1.50])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 2.08, S.E. = 7.35, p = 0.778, 95% CI [-12.33, 16.48]; Std. beta = 0.25, 95% CI [-1.49, 1.99])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 11.87, S.E. = 9.72, p = 0.222, 95% CI [-7.18, 30.93]; Std. beta = 1.43, 95% CI [-0.87, 3.73])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
